What is R?

R is a language and environment for statistical computing and graphics. For more details on using R language see https://www.r-project.org/about.html.

Installation of R and RStudio

https://rstudio-education.github.io/hopr/starting.html

Why R ?

Variables in R

first_num = 10
second_text <- "12"

class(first_num)
## [1] "numeric"
class(second_text)
## [1] "character"

Basic Mathemetical Operations

# Addition
2+1
## [1] 3
# Subtraction
2-1
## [1] 1
# Multiplication
2*3
## [1] 6
# Division
3/2
## [1] 1.5
# Exponentials
9^(1/2)
## [1] 3
# Modulus
33%%4
## [1] 1

Logical Operators

  • < Less Than

  • Greater Than

  • <= Less Than or Equal To

  • = Greater Than or Equal To

  • == Exactly Equal To
  • != Not Equal To
  • !x Not x
  • x&y x AND y
  • x|y x OR y
x = 24
y = 3

x<y
## [1] FALSE
x>y
## [1] TRUE
x==y
## [1] FALSE
x|y
## [1] TRUE

Create a variable

num_variable <- 23

num_variable
## [1] 23

Data Types

We look at character, numeric, integer, complex and logical data types

# Character
chr_var <- "Football"
# check the data type
class(chr_var)
## [1] "character"
# Numeric
num_var <- 23.3
class(num_var)
## [1] "numeric"
# Integer
int_var <- 2L
class(int_var)
## [1] "integer"
# complex
comp_var <- 2+3i
class(comp_var)
## [1] "complex"
# Convert between types
num_to_int <- as.integer(num_var)
class(num_to_int)
## [1] "integer"
# Logical
is_present <- TRUE

Data Structures

Data structures in R includes vector, list, matrix, array, factors, data frame and tibble

Vector

  • is the most common and basic data structure in R
  • common type or mode could be character, logical, integer or numeric.
  • all elements are the same type or implicit coercion occurs
name_vector <- c("Ada","Bello","Joy","Kelvin","Itunu")
class(name_vector)
## [1] "character"
name_vector[2]
## [1] "Bello"
name_vector[2:4]
## [1] "Bello"  "Joy"    "Kelvin"
# or 
name_vector <- vector() # vector("numeric", length = 10)

num_vec <- 1:20

# What happens if there are multiple data types of elements in a vector?
mixed_vec <- c("Ada", 28, "married", FALSE) # Implicit coercion
class(mixed_vec)
## [1] "character"

List

  • generic vector with different data types
student_list <- list(name=c("Ada","Bimbo","Aisha","Eze"),
                     age=c(24,25,30,45), 
                     marital_status=c("Single", "Married", "Divorced", 
                                      "Married"), 
                     is_student=c(TRUE,FALSE,FALSE,TRUE))

student_list
## $name
## [1] "Ada"   "Bimbo" "Aisha" "Eze"  
## 
## $age
## [1] 24 25 30 45
## 
## $marital_status
## [1] "Single"   "Married"  "Divorced" "Married" 
## 
## $is_student
## [1]  TRUE FALSE FALSE  TRUE
# Slicing List
student_list[2]
## $age
## [1] 24 25 30 45
student_list[[2]][1]
## [1] 24
student_list[["is_student"]][2]
## [1] FALSE
# What is the difference between using single and double square brackets?
class(student_list["is_student"])
## [1] "list"
class(student_list[["is_student"]])
## [1] "logical"

Matrix

  • vector with 2 dimensional, rectangular layout
  • same data type
mat_str <- matrix(c(1:20), 4,5) # define matrix with 4 rows and 5 columns
mat_str
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] [,5]
## [1,]    1    5    9   13   17
## [2,]    2    6   10   14   18
## [3,]    3    7   11   15   19
## [4,]    4    8   12   16   20
# dimension of matrix
dim(mat_str)
## [1] 4 5
# assigning column and row names
dimnames(mat_str) <- list(c("row1","row2","row3","row4"),
                          c("col1","col2","col3","col4","col5"))

rownames(mat_str) <- c("r1","r2","r3","r4")
colnames(mat_str) <- c("c1","c2","c3","c4","c5")

dimnames(mat_str)
## [[1]]
## [1] "r1" "r2" "r3" "r4"
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] "c1" "c2" "c3" "c4" "c5"
mat_str
##    c1 c2 c3 c4 c5
## r1  1  5  9 13 17
## r2  2  6 10 14 18
## r3  3  7 11 15 19
## r4  4  8 12 16 20
# What if the values are less than or more than the specified dimension?
mat_str <- matrix(c(1:20), 4,7)
## Warning in matrix(c(1:20), 4, 7): data length [20] is not a sub-multiple or
## multiple of the number of columns [7]
mat_str <- matrix(c(1:20), 4,3)
## Warning in matrix(c(1:20), 4, 3): data length [20] is not a sub-multiple or
## multiple of the number of columns [3]
# What if no dimension was specified?
#mat_str <- matrix(c(1:20))

# select value in column 1, row 3
mat_str[3]
## [1] 3
# select all values in row 3
mat_str[3,]
## [1]  3  7 11
# select all values in column 3
mat_str[,3]
## [1]  9 10 11 12
# select value in row 1, column 3. That is, 9
mat_str[1,3]
## [1] 9
# Selecting values from multiple columns and rows
mat_str <- matrix(c(1:20), 4,5)
mat_str[c(2:4),]
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] [,5]
## [1,]    2    6   10   14   18
## [2,]    3    7   11   15   19
## [3,]    4    8   12   16   20
mat_str[,c(1:3)]
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    1    5    9
## [2,]    2    6   10
## [3,]    3    7   11
## [4,]    4    8   12

Arrays

  • holds multi-dimensional data
arr_str <- array(c(1:21), dim=c(2,5)) # What happened?
arr_str # difference compared to matrix in structure flexibility
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] [,5]
## [1,]    1    3    5    7    9
## [2,]    2    4    6    8   10

Data frame

  • similar to a matrix in appearance
  • multiple types of data like a list
  • each column contain the same type of data or it defaults to character type in R
name <- c("Kemi", "Bala", "John", "Ike", "Shola", "Yoyo", "Ameenat", "Ijeoma")
age <- c(27,36, 13, 20, 19, 34, 29, 20)
marital_status <- c(TRUE, T, F, FALSE, TRUE, T, T, F)
students <- data.frame(name, age, marital_status)
students
##      name age marital_status
## 1    Kemi  27           TRUE
## 2    Bala  36           TRUE
## 3    John  13          FALSE
## 4     Ike  20          FALSE
## 5   Shola  19           TRUE
## 6    Yoyo  34           TRUE
## 7 Ameenat  29           TRUE
## 8  Ijeoma  20          FALSE

Add rows or columns to data frame

rbind(students, c("Eze", 22, TRUE))
##      name age marital_status
## 1    Kemi  27           TRUE
## 2    Bala  36           TRUE
## 3    John  13          FALSE
## 4     Ike  20          FALSE
## 5   Shola  19           TRUE
## 6    Yoyo  34           TRUE
## 7 Ameenat  29           TRUE
## 8  Ijeoma  20          FALSE
## 9     Eze  22           TRUE
cbind(students, "state")

## 2    Bala  36           TRUE   state
## 3    John  13          FALSE   state
## 4     Ike  20          FALSE   state
## 5   Shola  19           TRUE   state
## 6    Yoyo  34           TRUE   state
## 7 Ameenat  29           TRUE   state
## 8  Ijeoma  20          FALSE   state
students[,"state"] <- c("Lagos", "FCT", "Kogi", "Abia", "Cross-River", "Kano", "Oyo", "Enugu")

students

## 4     Ike  20          FALSE        Abia
## 5   Shola  19           TRUE Cross-River
## 6    Yoyo  34           TRUE        Kano
## 7 Ameenat  29           TRUE         Oyo
## 8  Ijeoma  20          FALSE       Enugu

## [1] "Bala"
students[2,3]
## [1] TRUE

Subsetting in data frame

students[students$age>20,]
##      name age marital_status state
## 1    Kemi  27           TRUE Lagos
## 2    Bala  36           TRUE   FCT
## 6    Yoyo  34           TRUE  Kano
## 7 Ameenat  29           TRUE   Oyo
students[students$age>20&students$state=="Oyo", ]
##      name age marital_status state
## 7 Ameenat  29           TRUE   Oyo
